Many games do this. I think most machines at the time had their patterns in RAM, and the NES was a rare exception that had many games with patterns stored in ROM.<br /><br />It was only natural that programmers would find some free time to update the patterns during gameplay for more dynamic graphics.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Thu May 24, 2007 3:52 pm</p><hr />
