<div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Turns out that, by taking some of the time of the rendered frame, I can simulate CHR bankswitching, in small chunks of 16 tiles per frame. I'm using this to update the main character, doing some background animations and so on.<br /></div><br />Yes, but this is almost cheating (i.e Battletoads  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=":wink:" title="Wink" /> )<br />I really think the best is to take the best from CHR ROM and CHR RAM, because both have their ups and downs, depending on what you want to show on the screen.</div><br />It's not cheating. It's what just about every game for Genesis, Super NES, and Game Boy Advance does. Seriously, back up your <em>Sonic Advance</em> or <em>Kirby: Nightmare in Dream Land</em> Game Pak, load it up in VisualBoyAdvance, open the pattern table viewer (Tools &gt; Tile Viewer), and turn on automatic refresh. Scroll down to 0x06010000 (sprite cel VRAM), make Sonic run and jump, and see what CHR changes. <a href="http://www.pineight.com/gba/managing-sprite-vram.txt" class="postlink">This white paper</a> was written near the beginning of the GBA homebrew scene.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon May 07, 2007 6:45 pm</p><hr />
